{"id":20591, "kind":"Bug", "createdAt":"2013-01-25T13:31:27.84338-08:00", "status":"Closed", "title":"apidoc for cts:not-in-query needs to be corrected/improved", "category":"documentation", "severity":"Major", "priority":{"level":"5", "title":""}, "submittedBy":{"username":"kcoleman", "name":"Kim Coleman", "email":"kim.coleman@marklogic.com"}, "assignTo":{"username":"nobody", "name":"nobody nobody", "email":"nobody@marklogic.com"}, "description":"I noticed the apidoc for cts:not-in-query appears to be almost a cut-n-paste from cts:and-not query, and as such doesn't accurately reflect what this query does or what the user needs to know about it. After talking to Mary about it, we should fix it on both 6.0 and latest. Mary's comments below:\r\n\r\nThere are some better points to be made here:\r\n(1) It depends on positions, so if you don't have the right kind of positions for the two subqueries, this query cannot be accurate via index resolution except (*)\r\n(2) If the either subquery is not accurate via index resolution alone, neither will the cts:not-in-query\r\n\r\nYou don't have to worry about false negatives like you do with cts:and-not-query, just false positives.\r\n\r\nExcept (*): What the functional spec says about intrinsically positionless queries vs happen-to-have-no-positions queries.\r\n\r\nOn the whole I think taking some of the material from the func spec and turning into English would be more useful than what's there now.\r\n\r\n", "samplequery":"", "sampledata":"", "version":"7.0-nightly", "tofixin":"6.0-3", "fixedin":"6.0-3", "platform":"all", "memory":"", "processors":"", "note":"", "subscribers":[{"username":"kcoleman", "name":"Kim Coleman", "email":"kim.coleman@marklogic.com"}], "attachments":[], "relationships":[{"type":"", "to":""}], "clones":[], "cloneOf":"", "support":{"headline":"", "supportDescription":"", "publishStatus":"Never Publish", "tickets":[], "customerImpact":{"level":"N/A", "title":""}, "workaround":""}, "tags":["documentation"